{"type":"user","uuid":"2d084f8d-d6f3-4ed8-b837-660149dfcf44","session_id":"62951781-27f6-43fd-92b7-2a78a8a15ac7","message":{"content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_c2a030ddbedc473d957c799c","content":[{"type":"text","text":"   1→DOC_LEVEL: L1\n   2→MODULE: runtime\n   3→PATH: src/**\n   4→DESCRIPTION: telegram + web request handling + sessioned CodeBuddy bridge\n   5→\n   6→ENTRYPOINT:\n   7→- src/index.js -> createHttpServer + optional Telegram bot launch\n   8→\n   9→KEY_FILES:\n  10→- src/config.js\n  11→- src/http/server.js\n  12→- src/routes/api-routes.js\n  13→- src/services/chat-service.js\n  14→- src/services/pipeline-control-service.js\n  15→- src/services/plan-ingestion-service.js\n  16→- src/pipeline-infra/config-loader.js\n  17→- src/pipeline-infra/script-runner.js\n  18→- src/adapters/codebuddy.js\n  19→- src/bot/telegram.js\n  20→- src/bot/commands/handlers/plan.js\n  21→- src/services/system-exec-service.js\n  22→\n  23→SUBDIRS:\n  24→- src/adapters -> (lazy) .prizm-docs/runtime/adapters.prizm\n  25→- src/bot -> (lazy) .prizm-docs/runtime/bot.prizm\n  26→- src/http -> (lazy) .prizm-docs/runtime/http.prizm\n  27→- src/routes -> (lazy) .prizm-docs/runtime/routes.prizm\n  28→- src/security -> (lazy) .prizm-docs/runtime/security.prizm\n  29→- src/services -> .prizm-docs/runtime/services.prizm\n  30→- src/pipeline-infra -> .prizm-docs/runtime/pipeline-infra.prizm\n  31→- src/utils -> (lazy) .prizm-docs/runtime/utils.prizm\n  32→\n  33→INTERFACES:\n  34→- HTTP: /healthz, /api/events(SSE), /api/chat, /api/chat/reset, /api/screenshot, /api/system/exec\n  35→- Telegram: /start, /help, /reset, /screenshot, /exec, /pipeline, /bugfix, /planner, /status, /logs, /stop, /plan, text message relay\n  36→\n  37→TRAPS:\n  38→- ENABLE_TELEGRAM=true requires TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN\n  39→- system exec is disabled unless ENABLE_SYSTEM_EXEC=true\n  40→- system exec requires ALLOWED_COMMAND_PREFIXES whitelist\n  41→- chat is serialized per session via chat-queue\n  42→\n  43→DECISIONS:\n  44→- 2026-03-09 | runtime-doc-init | model first-pass runtime map from source + API surface\n  45→- 2026-03-10 | runtime-infra-f001 | expose pipeline infra config in src/config.js and pipeline-control-service API for feature/bugfix run/status/stop/retry/logs/reset\n  46→- 2026-03-12 | runtime-f002 | add command routing layer for pipeline commands (/pipeline, /bugfix, /planner, /status, /logs, /stop)\n  47→- 2026-03-12 | runtime-f003 | add plan ingestion service for feature-list/bug-fix-list upload, validation, version management, and /plan command\n  48→"}],"is_error":false}],"role":"user"},"parent_tool_use_id":"019cde9a27c9893535be7a1bd386ddf8","__timestamp":"2026-03-11T20:33:25.070Z","_requestId":"9a060372b45d4f5a90dab23b747027c6"}
{"type":"assistant","uuid":"20260312043325cade02c6d6cd4e56","session_id":"62951781-27f6-43fd-92b7-2a78a8a15ac7","message":{"id":"20260312043325cade02c6d6cd4e56","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_aa3a4f0c739e44e6b0451258","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/loneyu/SelfProjects/PrizmClaw/.codebuddy/skills/prizmkit-analyze/SKILL.md"}}],"model":"glm-5.0","role":"assistant","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"type":"message","usage":{"input_tokens":26056,"output_tokens":58,"cache_creation_input_tokens":null,"cache_read_input_tokens":null,"cache_creation":null,"server_tool_use":null,"service_tier":null}},"parent_tool_use_id":"019cde9a27c9893535be7a1bd386ddf8","__timestamp":"2026-03-11T20:33:28.113Z","_requestId":"9a060372b45d4f5a90dab23b747027c6"}
{"type":"user","uuid":"b4d26196-26e4-4a37-bb98-52835079d0f6","session_id":"62951781-27f6-43fd-92b7-2a78a8a15ac7","message":{"content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_aa3a4f0c739e44e6b0451258","content":[{"type":"text","text":"   1→---\n   2→name: prizmkit-analyze\n   3→description: Cross-document consistency analysis for spec.md, plan.md, and tasks.md. Detects duplications, ambiguities, gaps, and rule conflicts. Read-only. (project)\n   4→---\n   5→\n   6→# PrizmKit Analyze\n   7→\n   8→Perform a non-destructive cross-artifact consistency and quality analysis across spec.md, plan.md, and tasks.md before implementation. Identifies duplications, ambiguities, underspecified items, rule conflicts, and coverage gaps.\n   9→\n  10→### When to Use\n  11→- After `prizmkit.plan` to validate spec-plan alignment before task generation\n  12→- After `prizmkit.tasks` to validate full spec-plan-tasks consistency before implementation\n  13→- User says \"analyze\", \"check consistency\", \"validate spec\", \"review plan\"\n  14→- Before `prizmkit.implement` as a quality gate\n  15→\n  16→## Commands\n  17→\n  18→### prizmkit.analyze\n  19→\n  20→Cross-document consistency analysis.\n  21→\n  22→**PRECONDITION:** `spec.md` and `plan.md` exist in `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/`. `tasks.md` is recommended but not required.\n  23→\n  24→## Operating Constraints\n  25→\n  26→**STRICTLY READ-ONLY**: Do **not** modify any files. Output a structured analysis report to conversation only. Offer an optional remediation plan (user must explicitly approve before any edits).\n  27→\n  28→**Prizm Rules Authority**: The project rules in `.prizm-docs/root.prizm` RULES section are **non-negotiable** within this analysis scope. Rule conflicts are automatically CRITICAL severity and require adjustment of the spec, plan, or tasks — not dilution or silent ignoring of the rule. If a rule itself needs to change, that must occur via a separate `prizmkit.doc.update`.\n  29→\n  30→## Execution Steps\n  31→\n  32→### Step 1: Initialize Analysis Context\n  33→\n  34→Locate the current feature directory in `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/` by checking the current Git branch name or scanning `.prizmkit/specs/` for the most recent feature directory.\n  35→\n  36→Derive absolute paths:\n  37→- SPEC = `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/spec.md`\n  38→- PLAN = `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/plan.md`\n  39→- TASKS = `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/tasks.md` (optional)\n  40→\n  41→Abort with an error message if spec.md or plan.md is missing — instruct the user to run the missing prerequisite command (`prizmkit.specify` or `prizmkit.plan`).\n  42→\n  43→If tasks.md is missing, proceed with spec+plan analysis only and note reduced coverage in the report.\n  44→\n  45→### Step 2: Load Artifacts (Progressive Disclosure)\n  46→\n  47→Load only the minimal necessary context from each artifact:\n  48→\n  49→**From spec.md:**\n  50→- Overview/Context\n  51→- Functional Requirements\n  52→- Non-Functional Requirements\n  53→- User Stories and Acceptance Criteria\n  54→- Scope Boundaries\n  55→- Edge Cases (if present)\n  56→\n  57→**From plan.md:**\n  58→- Architecture/stack choices\n  59→- Component Design\n  60→- Data Model references\n  61→- API Contracts\n  62→- Testing Strategy\n  63→- Risk Assessment\n  64→\n  65→**From tasks.md (if exists):**\n  66→- Task IDs and Descriptions\n  67→- Phase grouping (Setup, Foundational, User Stories, Polish)\n  68→- Parallel markers `[P]`\n  69→- Referenced file paths\n  70→\n  71→**From .prizm-docs/root.prizm:**\n  72→- RULES section (MUST/NEVER/PREFER directives)\n  73→- PATTERNS section (project-wide code patterns)\n  74→- TECH_STACK section (for consistency checking)\n  75→\n  76→### Step 3: Build Semantic Models\n  77→\n  78→Create internal representations (do not include raw artifacts in output):\n  79→\n  80→- **Requirements inventory**: Each functional + non-functional requirement with a stable key (derive slug from imperative phrase; e.g., \"User can upload file\" -> `user-can-upload-file`)\n  81→- **User story/action inventory**: Discrete user actions with acceptance criteria\n  82→- **Task coverage mapping**: Map each task to one or more requirements or stories (inference by keyword / explicit reference patterns like IDs or key phrases)\n  83→- **Prizm rule set**: Extract MUST/NEVER/PREFER normative statements from root.prizm RULES\n  84→\n  85→### Step 4: Detection Passes\n  86→\n  87→Focus on high-signal findings. Limit to **50 findings total**; aggregate remainder in overflow summary.\n  88→\n  89→#### A. Duplication Detection\n  90→- Identify near-duplicate requirements across spec.md sections\n  91→- Mark lower-quality phrasing for consolidation\n  92→\n  93→#### B. Ambiguity Detection\n  94→- Flag vague adjectives (fast, scalable, secure, intuitive, robust) lacking measurable criteria\n  95→- Flag unresolved placeholders (TODO, TBD, ???, `<placeholder>`, `[NEEDS CLARIFICATION]`)\n  96→\n  97→#### C. Underspecification\n  98→- Requirements with verbs but missing object or measurable outcome\n  99→- User stories missing acceptance criteria alignment\n 100→- Tasks referencing files or components not defined in spec/plan\n 101→- Plan components with no corresponding spec requirement\n 102→\n 103→#### D. Prizm Rules Alignment\n 104→- Any requirement or plan element conflicting with a MUST/NEVER directive\n 105→- Missing mandated patterns from PATTERNS section\n 106→- Tech stack inconsistencies between plan and root.prizm TECH_STACK\n 107→\n 108→#### E. Coverage Gaps\n 109→- Requirements with zero associated tasks (if tasks.md loaded)\n 110→- Tasks with no mapped requirement/story (\"orphan tasks\")\n 111→- Non-functional requirements not reflected in tasks (performance, security, etc.)\n 112→- User stories without corresponding plan components\n 113→\n 114→#### F. Inconsistency\n 115→- Terminology drift (same concept named differently across files)\n 116→- Data entities referenced in plan but absent in spec (or vice versa)\n 117→- Task ordering contradictions (e.g., integration tasks before foundational setup without dependency note)\n 118→- Conflicting requirements (e.g., one requires REST while other specifies GraphQL)\n 119→\n 120→### Step 5: Severity Assignment\n 121→\n 122→Use this heuristic to prioritize findings:\n 123→\n 124→- **CRITICAL**: Violates Prizm RULES MUST/NEVER directive, missing core artifact section, or requirement with zero coverage that blocks baseline functionality\n 125→- **HIGH**: Duplicate or conflicting requirement, ambiguous security/performance attribute, untestable acceptance criterion\n 126→- **MEDIUM**: Terminology drift, missing non-functional task coverage, underspecified edge case\n 127→- **LOW**: Style/wording improvements, minor redundancy not affecting execution order\n 128→\n 129→### Step 6: Produce Compact Analysis Report\n 130→\n 131→Output a Markdown report (**no file writes**) with the following structure:\n 132→\n 133→```\n 134→## Consistency Analysis Report\n 135→\n 136→| ID | Category | Severity | Location(s) | Summary | Recommendation |\n 137→|----|----------|----------|-------------|---------|----------------|\n 138→| A1 | Duplication | HIGH | spec.md §2.1, §3.4 | Two similar requirements... | Merge phrasing; keep clearer version |\n 139→| D1 | Rules Alignment | CRITICAL | plan.md §Architecture | Conflicts with MUST rule... | Adjust plan to align with rule |\n 140→\n 141→**Coverage Summary:**\n 142→\n 143→| Requirement Key | Has Task? | Task IDs | Notes |\n 144→|-----------------|-----------|----------|-------|\n 145→\n 146→**Prizm Rules Alignment Issues:** (if any)\n 147→\n 148→**Unmapped Tasks:** (if any)\n 149→\n 150→**Metrics:**\n 151→- Total Requirements: N\n 152→- Total Tasks: N\n 153→- Coverage %: N% (requirements with >=1 task)\n 154→- Ambiguity Count: N\n 155→- Duplication Count: N\n 156→- Critical Issues: N\n 157→```\n 158→\n 159→### Step 7: Provide Next Actions\n 160→\n 161→At end of report, output a concise Next Actions block:\n 162→\n 163→- If CRITICAL issues exist: **Recommend resolving before `prizmkit.implement`**\n 164→- If only LOW/MEDIUM: User may proceed, but provide improvement suggestions\n 165→- Provide explicit command suggestions:\n 166→  - \"Run `prizmkit.specify` to refine requirements\"\n 167→  - \"Run `prizmkit.plan` to adjust architecture\"\n 168→  - \"Edit tasks.md to add coverage for requirement X\"\n 169→  - \"Proceed to `prizmkit.implement`\" (if clean)\n 170→\n 171→### Step 8: Offer Remediation\n 172→\n 173→Ask the user: \"Would you like me to suggest concrete remediation edits for the top N issues?\" (Do NOT apply them automatically.)\n 174→\n 175→## Operating Principles\n 176→\n 177→### Context Efficiency\n 178→- **Minimal high-signal tokens**: Focus on actionable findings, not exhaustive documentation\n 179→- **Progressive disclosure**: Load artifacts incrementally; don't dump all content into analysis\n 180→- **Token-efficient output**: Limit findings table to 50 rows; summarize overflow\n 181→- **Deterministic results**: Rerunning without changes should produce consistent IDs and counts\n 182→\n 183→### Analysis Guidelines\n 184→- **NEVER modify files** (this is read-only analysis)\n 185→- **NEVER hallucinate missing sections** (if absent, report them accurately)\n 186→- **Prioritize Prizm Rules violations** (these are always CRITICAL)\n 187→- **Use examples over exhaustive rules** (cite specific instances, not generic patterns)\n 188→- **Report zero issues gracefully** (emit success report with coverage statistics)\n 189→\n 190→**HANDOFF:** `prizmkit.implement` (if clean) or `prizmkit.specify` / `prizmkit.plan` / `prizmkit.tasks` (if issues found)\n 191→\n 192→## Output\n 193→\n 194→Analysis report is output to conversation only. No files are created or modified.\n 195→"}],"is_error":false}],"role":"user"},"parent_tool_use_id":"019cde9a27c9893535be7a1bd386ddf8","__timestamp":"2026-03-11T20:33:28.122Z","_requestId":"9a060372b45d4f5a90dab23b747027c6"}
{"type":"user","uuid":"7224d96d-55d5-4748-a672-79fa6f17ebd3","session_id":"62951781-27f6-43fd-92b7-2a78a8a15ac7","message":{"content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"019cde9a27c9893535be7a1bd386ddf8","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have all the context needed. Let me perform the cross-document consistency analysis following the prizmkit-analyze workflow.\n\n---\n\n## Consistency Analysis Report: F-006 Safety and Permission Guard\n\n### Detection Passes\n\n| ID | Category | Severity | Location(s) | Summary | Recommendation |\n|----|----------|----------|-------------|---------|----------------|\n| I1 | Inconsistency | **MEDIUM** | spec.md:44 / plan.md:107-124 | AC-3.4 specifies `sanitizePath()` and `sanitizeTargetId()` functions, but plan.md interface only defines `sanitizeParam()` and `validatePath()` | Rename functions in plan.md to match spec, or update spec AC-3.4 to match plan interface |\n| I2 | Coverage Gap | **MEDIUM** | spec.md:62 / plan.md:233-237 | AC-5.3 requires \"按会话 ID 或用户 ID 检索审计记录的 API\", but plan.md `queryAuditLogs()` only supports userId, action, startDate, endDate — missing sessionId filter | Add sessionId to queryAuditLogs filters in plan.md |\n| I3 | Underspecification | **LOW** | spec.md:52 / plan.md:156 | AC-4.2 \"确认消息包含操作摘要和风险提示\" lacks concrete message template; plan.md §C-3 shows `message: string` but no content defined | Add confirmation message template to spec or plan |\n| I4 | Inconsistency | **LOW** | spec.md:30 vs plan.md:89 | AC-2.1 lists `exec` as high-risk command, but plan.md §C-1 HIGH_RISK_COMMANDS omits `exec` from the set (shows: stop, reset, retry, exec, force-unlock) — **CORRECTION**: Actually it IS included on line 89. No issue. | N/A — false positive |\n| I5 | Terminology Drift | **LOW** | spec.md:23 / plan.md:49 | spec uses \"getUserPermission(userId)\", plan uses \"getUserRole(userId)\" — function name mismatch | Align terminology: rename to `getUserRole` in spec or `getUserPermission` in plan |\n| I6 | Coverage Gap | **MEDIUM** | tasks.md:153-158 / spec.md:62 | AC-5.3 requires API for querying audit logs by session/user ID, but T-108 `/audit` command task doesn't mention sessionId filter support | Extend T-108 acceptance criteria to include sessionId filter |\n| D1 | Duplication | **LOW** | spec.md:86-94 / plan.md:76-87 | Command permission matrix defined twice (spec High-Risk Command Matrix + plan COMMAND_MIN_ROLE) — acceptable redundancy for reference | Keep both but ensure consistency; currently aligned ✓ |\n| A1 | Ambiguity | **LOW** | spec.md:74 | NFR-4 \"审计日志不可被普通用户访问\" — \"普通用户\" is vague; could mean unauthenticated users or non-admin users | Clarify: is this `viewer` role or unauthenticated? |\n| A2 | Ambiguity | **LOW** | spec.md:30-31 | AC-2.1 high-risk commands list includes `exec`, but AC-2.4 says exec is controlled by `ENABLE_SYSTEM_EXEC` — is exec \"high-risk\" when the feature is disabled? | Clarify behavior: should exec be rejected before or after ENABLE_SYSTEM_EXEC check? |\n\n---\n\n### Coverage Summary\n\n| Requirement Key | Has Task? | Task IDs | Notes |\n|-----------------|-----------|----------|-------|\n| US-1 Permission Tiers | ✓ | T-001, T-002, T-010, T-011, T-101 | Full coverage |\n| US-2 Command Authorization | ✓ | T-102, T-010 | Full coverage |\n| US-3 Parameter Sanitization | ✓ | T-012, T-013, T-103 | Full coverage |\n| US-4 Confirmation Flow | ✓ | T-014, T-015, T-104, T-105, T-106 | Full coverage |\n| US-5 Audit Logging | ✓ | T-016, T-017, T-107, T-108 | Full coverage |\n| NFR-1 Performance | ⚠ | Implicit in implementation | No explicit performance test task |\n| NFR-2 Reliability | ⚠ | Implicit in implementation | No explicit reliability test task |\n| NFR-3 Maintainability | ✓ | T-902, T-903 | Documentation tasks |\n| NFR-4 Security | ⚠ | T-103 covers sanitization | No explicit security test task |\n\n---\n\n### Prizm Rules Alignment Issues\n\n**No RULES section found in root.prizm** — Only TRAPS present:\n- `ENABLE_TELEGRAM=true requires TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` — Not applicable to F-006\n- `system exec is disabled unless ENABLE_SYSTEM_EXEC=true` — **Aligned**: spec.md AC-2.4 addresses this\n- `system exec requires ALLOWED_COMMAND_PREFIXES whitelist` — **Aligned**: spec references this constraint\n\n**No CRITICAL rule violations detected.**\n\n---\n\n### Unmapped Tasks\n\n| Task ID | Summary | Issue |\n|---------|---------|-------|\n| None | All tasks map to requirements | ✓ Clean mapping |\n\n---\n\n### Metrics\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Total Requirements (User Stories) | 5 |\n| Total Acceptance Criteria | 18 |\n| Total Tasks | 22 |\n| Coverage % | **100%** (all US have >=1 task) |\n| Ambiguity Count | 2 |\n| Duplication Count | 1 (acceptable) |\n| Inconsistency Count | 2 |\n| Coverage Gap Count | 2 |\n| **Critical Issues** | **0** |\n\n---\n\n## Next Actions\n\n### Verdict: ✅ PASS WITH WARNINGS\n\n**No CRITICAL issues found.** The spec/plan/tasks are consistent enough to proceed with implementation.\n\n### Recommended Improvements (Optional):\n\n1. **I1 (MEDIUM)**: Align function names between spec and plan:\n   - Option A: Update spec AC-3.4 to use `sanitizeParam()` and `validatePath()`\n   - Option B: Update plan interface to add `sanitizeTargetId()` alias\n\n2. **I2 (MEDIUM)**: Add `sessionId` filter to `queryAuditLogs()` interface in plan.md:\n   ```javascript\n   // Add to filters parameter\n   @param {string} [filters.sessionId]\n   ```\n\n3. **I5 (LOW)**: Standardize terminology — recommend using `getUserRole()` throughout (matches plan and is more precise)\n\n4. **A1-A2 (LOW)**: Clarify ambiguous terms in spec before implementation\n\n---\n\n## COMPLETION_SIGNAL\n\n```\n{\n  \"agent\": \"reviewer\",\n  \"phase\": \"Phase 4 - Cross-Check\",\n  \"feature\": \"F-006\",\n  \"slug\": \"006-safety-and-permission-guard\",\n  \"verdict\": \"PASS_WITH_WARNINGS\",\n  \"critical_count\": 0,\n  \"high_count\": 0,\n  \"medium_count\": 3,\n  \"low_count\": 4,\n  \"recommendation\": \"Proceed to implementation. Optional improvements can be addressed during dev or deferred.\"\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**No CRITICAL issues remain.** The spec/plan/tasks for F-006 are ready for implementation via `prizmkit.implement`.\n\n[Agent ID: agent-8cb73c5c]"}],"is_error":false}],"role":"user"},"parent_tool_use_id":"019cde9a27c9893535be7a1bd386ddf8","__timestamp":"2026-03-11T20:34:20.567Z","_requestId":"9a060372b45d4f5a90dab23b747027c6"}
